Laravel Tests "Feature" and "Unit" testing

2022.09.18 by Murad Shaker

The first step is to download laravel through this command

composer create-project laravel/laravel example-app

Now in Laravel, the “tests” folder is the place for the basic tests in Laravel, and there are several tests in this folder. In this article, we will focus on “features” testing and “unit” testing

"Feature" tests are used to interact with the database. For example, you have created the (comments) feature in your application. ‘You may want to check whether this feature works as expected or not. You can call the function inside the Controller file that inserts the comment into the database. And to make sure that it works as expected or not, and also the "feature" test is used with HTTP requests. You can call HTTP requests from within the "feature" file directly or connect to the paths that are located in the  Web. php  file and Interaction with them Unlike in "Unit" test , you can't do that in "Unit" test

To make this understandable, I will create a simple project and I will use feature testing in this project

Now create a (Migration file) table  for comments,

type this command
php artisan make:migration create_comments_table

This command creates a Migration file, in the migrations folder in the  "database\migrations"  directory

 Go to the migration file we just created. It should look like this

Type the following command to migrate these columns to the database

 php artisan migrate 

The database should look like this
Now type this command to create a Controller file
 php artisan make:Controller CommentController 

Type the following command to create a Model file
 php artisan make:Model CommentModel

This file gives us the ability to connect directly to the database and enables us to specify table column names for the comments table. They can be used in the CommentController file or any part in laravel.,Where you can work from a specific table, for example, updating the record, deleting the record, inserting data, and so on

Don't forget to import the CommentModel class into the controller file

Create a function inside the CommentController file
in this way

public function storeC (Request $request){

        $comment = new CommentModel([
                'user_name' => $request->input(),
                 'comment' => $request->input(),
        ]);

       $comment->save();
}

 

Now go to the  web.php  paths file and include these lines in the  web.php  file

 use App\Http\Controllers\CommentController; 
 Route::post( "/seComment", [CommentController::class, 'storeC']); 
-------
After these steps, now go to the feature  test folder , specifically to the ExampleText.php file
Create a function with this name  testUserCanCreateComment()  As shown below

public function testUserCanCreateComment()
{
   $response = $this->post('/seComment', [

      'V_USER_NAME' => 'Mark',
      'V_USER_COMMENT' => 'Looks great', 

   ]);
}

Don't forget to import the "ModelComment" class here, as shown

You might say I don't understand

$response =  $this->post('/seComment', [
'V_USER_NAME' => 'Mark',
'V_USER_COMMENT' => 'Looks great', 
])

It simply selects where you want to send the name and comment to. We have now sent the name and comment to the function "storeC" in the CommentController with pathname "/seCommen"

The process behind the scenes is like this

After that, go to the CommentController file to receive 'Name' and 'Comment'.
in this way

To explain these steps to you effectively, see the following image
The process takes place behind the scenes with the same steps shown in this picture

I think you understand

Now the function is ready to work and I will check it by testing the feature whether it works correctly or not, now write this command to run the test

 php artisan test 

As shown in the picture, 

it says that the comment and name have been inserted into the database, and the storeC function is working correctly

Now we will check using the feature test whether we may be redirected to a specific path when the name and comment are entered into the database

Go to the  CommentController.php  file

Add the following line at the bottom of the "storeC" function as shown below
 return redirect('/comments'); 

Now it is clear that when the name and comment are sent to the database, we will be redirected to the "/comments" path.
Now go back to the feature test file "ExampleTest.php" and add the following line inside the testUserCanCreateComment function

 $response->assertRedirect('/comments'); 

Remember: When we are redirected to the “/comments” path, this is evidence that the comment and name were sent to the database successfully.

Now we want to know whether we are redirected to the “/comments” path or not when we run the test
Type a command

 php artisan test 

If you want to check whether a specific value exists in the database or not, you can use the assertDatabaseHas function

 $this->assertDatabaseHas('comments',[ 
   'user_name' => 'mark',
    'comment' => 'Looks great',  
 ]);

Now run the test to check whether the specified data exists or not

 php artisan test 

The test was successful indicating that the specified data is present in the "Comments" table.

Now we will go to explain and clarify the Unit test.

In general, this "Unit" test is used to examine the methods that you want to create that have nothing to do with the database. It is simple ways to test the methods that you have created. For example, I have a project that I want to create a function for a specific purpose in the project, for example a function to remove spaces from the string: In this case, I will create this function, and upon completion I want to make sure that it works as required or expected

Now create a file in laravel's App folder in the traditional way 
as shown in the image

1

2

3

4

To be like this

?php

  namespace App;

  class testUnitEXM {

   public function Clear_white_spaces_from_the_string($text)
    {
       
    }

}

Now go to the unit test file “Unit”  ExampleTest.php 
Import the class into  testUnitEXM.php 

Go back to the testUnitEXM.php  file and include these lines inside the "Clear_white_spaces_from_the_string()" function.

 return str_replace("" , $text);

This function removes white spaces from a specified string

Go back to the testUnitEXM.php  file and  Add these two lines inside the "test_that_true_is_true" function 

$obToNEWtext = new testUnitEXM();
$newText = $obToNEWtext->Clear_white_spaces_from_the_string("h   e   11    o");

We passed this string "h   e   11    o" to the "Clear_white_spaces_from_the_string()" function in order to make sure it works correctly or not (My intention is for the Clear_white_spaces_from_the_string() function to return "hello" with no white spaces)
The purpose of this function is to check the  function whether it is working properly or not (removing white spaces from the string)

Now add the function assertEquals()

 $this->assertEquals("hello", $newText); 

This method is used to check whether the "hello" text specified in this method matches the value coming from the target function.
In this case, if the values are equal, this is evidence that the white spaces have been deleted from “h e 11 o” and that the “Clear_white_spaces_from_the_string” function is working correctly as expected.

This picture explains it to you

NOTE :: When you create a function inside a Unit test file, it must start with "_test"   For example "test_NameMethod", "test_NameFunction"

Now to test, type the command  "php artisan test" 
Note: There are many functions that are used with unit testing, such as “assertEquals” and others, you can search for

As you can see, the test passed 😁
Now, by implementing these steps, I think you have understood what the meaning of unit testing is, simply that it is a test intended for individual functions or something like that, as we did above.
